2 Descriptive satistics (15pt)

  1. (3pt) How many countries are there in the dataset? Analyze all three: iso3, iso2 and name.

The gapminder data has 3 variables representing countries iso3, iso2, and name

iso3 has 253 unique values

iso2 has 249 unique values

name has 250 unique values

  1. If you did this correctly, you saw that there are more names than iso-2 codes, and there are even more iso3 -codes. What is going on? Can you find it out?
  1. (5pt) Find how many names are there for each iso-2 code. Are there any iso-2 codes that correspond to more than one name? What are these countries?
gapminder %>%
  group_by(iso2) %>%
  summarise(num = n_distinct(name)) %>%
  filter(num > 1)
## # A tibble: 1 × 2
##   iso2    num
##   <chr> <int>
## 1 <NA>      2

Yes, from the code segment output above we see that the only iso-2 code that correspond to more than one name is ‘NA’ (or ‘missing’). This means that there are two different country names with the iso-2 field missing. Other than this, all other iso-2 codes correspond to only 1 country name.

  1. (5pt) Now repeat the same for name and iso3-code. Are there country names that have more than one iso3-code? What are these countries?
gapminder %>%
  group_by(name) %>%
  summarise(num = n_distinct(iso3)) %>%
  filter(num > 1)
## # A tibble: 1 × 2
##   name    num
##   <chr> <int>
## 1 <NA>      4

Yes, from the code segment output above we see that the only country name that has more than one iso_3 code is ‘NA’ (or missing). From this we can tell that there are 4 ‘missing’ values in the name field, however, each of them still have/are assigned a different iso-3 codes.

Hint: two of these entitites are CHANISL and NLD CURACAO.

3 CO2 Emmisions

Next, let’s analyze CO2 emissions.

  1. (2pt) How many missing co2 emissions are there for each year? Analyze both missing CO2 and co2_PC. Which years have most missing data?
gapminder %>%
  group_by(time) %>%
  select(time, co2, co2_PC) %>%
  filter(!is.na(time)) %>%
  summarise(co2_na = sum(is.na(co2)), co2_PC_na = sum(is.na(co2_PC))) %>%
  mutate(sum = co2_na + co2_PC_na) %>%
  arrange(desc(sum))

  1. (5pt) Make a plot of total CO2 emissions over time for the U.S, China, and India. Add a few more countries of your choice. Explain what do you see.
gapminder %>%
  select(name, time, co2) %>%
  filter(!is.na(co2)) %>%
  filter(name %in% c("Japan", "China", "India", "United States of America", "Russian Federation")) %>%
  ggplot(aes(time, co2 / 1000000, col=name)) + 
  geom_line() +
  labs(title = "Total CO2 Emission per Year",
       x = "Time (Year)", 
       y = "CO2 Emission (Million kt)", 
       col = "Country Name")

The graph depicts the countries with the highest CO2 Emmisions (kt). From this, we see that China has the highest amount of CO2 emmisions, with the U.S. coming in second amongst the 5 countries for CO2 emmisions. After the year 2000, Russia Japan, and India all hover around the same amount of CO2 emmisions. This graph may indicate a positive relationship between population size and CO2 emmisions

  1. (5pt) Now let’s analyze the CO2 emissions per capita (co2_PC ). Make a similar plot of the same countries. What does this figure suggest?
gapminder %>%
  select(name, time, co2_PC) %>%
  filter(!is.na(co2_PC)) %>%
  filter(name %in% c("Japan", "China", "India", "United States of America", "Russian Federation")) %>%
  ggplot(aes(time, co2_PC, col=name)) + 
  geom_line() +
  labs(title = "CO2 Emission per Capita per Year",
       x = "Time (Year)", 
       y = "CO2 Emission Per Capita (Metric Tons per Capita)", 
       col = "Country Name")

This graph depicts the amount of CO2 emission per person in a country. China actually has a lower overall CO2 emission per capita compared to other countries (besides India). This is interesting because when comparing this graph to the previous one, China has the largest overall CO2 Emission per year. This suggests that there is a positive relationship between population size and total CO2 emission per year.

  1. (7pt) Make a barplot where you show the previous results–average CO2 emissions per capita across continents in 1960 and 2016.
avg_co2 <- gapminder %>%
  select(region, co2_PC, time) %>%
  filter(!is.na(region), time %in% c("1960", "2016")) %>%
  group_by(region, time) %>%
  summarise(avg_co2_PC = mean(co2_PC, na.rm = TRUE))

ggplot(avg_co2, aes(region, avg_co2_PC, fill=factor(time))) +
  geom_col(position = "dodge") +
  labs(title = "Average CO2 per Capita Across Regions (Continents)",
       x = "Region (Continent Name)",
       y = "Average CO2 per Capita (Metric Ton per Capita)",
       col = "Time (Year)")

4 GDP per capita (50pt)

Let’s look at GDP per capita (GDP_PC ).

  1. (8pt) Make a scatterplot of GDP per capita versus life expectancy by country, using data for
  2. Make the point size dependent on the country size, and color those according to the continent. Feel free to adjust the plot in other ways to make it better. Comment what do you see there.
gdp_PC <- gapminder %>%
  group_by(name) %>%
  select(region, GDP_PC, lifeExpectancy, totalPopulation, time) %>%
  filter(time == "1960", !is.na(GDP_PC), !is.na(lifeExpectancy))

ggplot(gdp_PC, aes(GDP_PC, lifeExpectancy, col = factor(region))) +
  geom_point(aes(size=totalPopulation / 1000000), alpha = 0.8) +
  labs(title = "Life Expectancy vs. GDP per Capita in 1960",
       x = "GDP per Capita",
       y = "Life Expentancy (Years)",
       col = "Region (Continents)",
       size = "Total Population (Millions)")

  1. (4pt) Make a similar plot, but this time use 2019 data only.
gdp_PC <- gapminder %>%
  group_by(name) %>%
  select(region, GDP_PC, lifeExpectancy, totalPopulation, time) %>%
  filter(time == "2019", !is.na(GDP_PC), !is.na(lifeExpectancy), !is.na(region))

ggplot(gdp_PC, aes(GDP_PC, lifeExpectancy, col = factor(region))) +

  1. (6pt) Compare these two plots and comment what do you see. How has world developed through the last 60 years?

For sure when looking at the two plots, there are a lot more countries in 2019 compared to in 1960. The overall GDP_PC has decreased, resulting in life expectancy to increase in almost every region / country. This can be because of factors like technology and access to medical support has improved through the last 60 years, which has greatly increased the overall expectancy of life.

  1. (6pt) Compute the average life expectancy for each continent in 1960 and 2019. Do the results fit with what do you see on the figures?

Note: here as average I mean just average over countries, ignore the fact that countries are of different size.

avg_LE <- gapminder %>%
  group_by(region, time) %>%
  select(region, time, lifeExpectancy) %>%
  filter(time %in% c("1960", "2019"), !is.na(region)) %>%
  summarise(avg_LE = mean(lifeExpectancy, na.rm = TRUE))

  1. (8pt) Compute the average LE growth from 1960-2019 across the continents. Show the results in the order of growth. Explain what do you see.

Hint: these data (data in long form) is not the simplest to compute growth. But you may want to check out the lag() function. And do not forget to group data by continent when using lag(), otherwise your results will be messed up!

avg_LE %>%
  group_by(region) %>%
  mutate(prev.val = lag(avg_LE)) %>%
  filter(row_number() %% 2 == 0) %>%
  mutate(avg_growth = avg_LE - prev.val) %>%
  summarise(region, avg_growth) %>%
  arrange(desc(avg_growth))
## # A tibble: 5 × 2
##   region   avg_growth
##   <chr>         <dbl>
## 1 Asia           23.0
## 2 Africa         22.6
## 3 Americas       17.2
## 4 Oceania        17.1
## 5 Europe         11.1
  1. (6pt) Show the histogram of GDP per capita for years of 1960 and 2019. Try to put both histograms on the same graph, see how well you can do it!
GDP_histogram <- gapminder %>%
  filter(time == "1960" | time == "2019", !is.na(GDP_PC))
ggplot(GDP_histogram, aes(GDP_PC, fill = factor(time))) +
  geom_histogram(alpha = 0.8, position = "dodge", bins = 30) +
  labs(title = "GDP per capita for years of 1960 and 2019",
       x = "GDP per Capita",
       y = "Count",
       fill = "Year")

  1. (6pt) What was the ranking of US in terms of life expectancy in 1960 and in 2019? (When counting from top.)

Hint: check out the function rank()!

Hint2: 17 for 1960.

ranks_per_year <- gapminder %>%
  select(name, lifeExpectancy, time) %>%
  filter(!is.na(lifeExpectancy), !is.na(name), time %in% c("1960", "2019")) %>%
  arrange(time, desc(lifeExpectancy)) %>%
  group_by(time) %>%
  mutate(rankings = rank(desc(lifeExpectancy)))

ranks_per_year %>%
  filter(name == "United States of America")
## # A tibble: 2 × 4
## # Groups:   time [2]
##   name                     lifeExpectancy  time rankings
##   <chr>                             <dbl> <dbl>    <dbl>
## 1 United States of America           69.8  1960       17
## 2 United States of America           78.8  2019       46
  1. (6pt) If you did this correctly, then you noticed that US ranking has been falling quite a bit. But we also have more countries in 2019–what about the relative rank divided by the corresponding number of countries that have LE data in the corresponding year?

Hint: 0.0904 for 1960.

ranks_per_year %>%
  select(name, time, rankings) %>%
  group_by(time) %>%
  mutate(total_n = max(rankings)) %>%
  filter(name == "United States of America") %>%
  summarise(rr_over_ncountries = rankings/total_n)
## # A tibble: 2 × 2
##    time rr_over_ncountries
##   <dbl>              <dbl>
## 1  1960             0.0904
## 2  2019             0.235
